At 7 years old, my daughter still plays with hers also.. Stacking them by numbers into pyramids, or just using her imagination to see what she can build. So there you go, at least 7 years of play (if you choose) and Gender neutral as my daughter and both of my sons now have their own set! Tons of different uses and can last several years.. Great price, very durable product, to grow with your children for years(:

text: i think this is by far one of the best toys i ever came across and am really happy i did buy it. i wanted to say "it is packed with fun and educational features" but then that wouldnt be accurate as these are really "hollow blocks" ...but all kidding aside...there is so much thought that was put into this product that i dont think there is more that could be had in this package:you get:1) soft texture- you dont have to be afraid of baby being hit or falling on these and hurting themself.2) durable construction- rubber3) reasonable size for small hands4) multiple (bright) colors to teach baby5) numerals6) animals (puppy, lion, duck, kittens, giraffe...)7) counting opportunity...i really am stumped for a better explanation right now. but what i really intend to say is that eg on the block numbered two (1 face) there are two lions (covering 4 faces) as well as two swirls (1 face) so not only can u teach the little ones to recognize the two lions but also u can learn to count based on the objects.most toys that i have come across stop counting at nine but this one goes to ten. so u have ten colors, numerals 1-10, ten different animals as well as item count according to the number on one block. and if that is not all- the hole in one side allows it to become a squeak toy as well.great buy really

text: Back when I was considering buying these for my one-year old and reading the reviews, I thought it was really silly that several people complained about the colors of these blocks. After all, the colors looked cute to me in the picture, and how much do color schemes really matter to a baby? I scoffed at those people. I even judged them a little. And today, I am becoming one of them. The colors truly are bad. There are several shades of orange, a couple ugly reds, and even a hot pink but NO GREEN. You can't even make a true rainbow with these blocks. And there is no way to organize them so that all the colors look nice next to one another. I'm not even sure what to call some of these shades. Trust me, when you are the one putting these blocks away every single night, these little things start to bug you.That being said, the design is pretty cool. They are soft, squeaky, and squeezable. There are numbers and really cute corresponding pictures on each one. I just can't seem to get my one year old terribly interested in them. Maybe he's not in the right phase of development for them right now. If he ever does start to really enjoy them, I'll certainly edit this review.

This makes hard toys impossible right now so I’m constantly on the search for soft colorful toys that she can grab and do her worst with.What I like about this toy as a mom:  1. While I have a ton of teething rings and other little teething toys, most of them are not too stimulating so he grows bored of them rather quickly.  I wanted to buy him something different - something that he could gnaw on, but also something that he would play with for longer than 10 seconds, so I bought these.  The blocks in this set are squishy, colorful and smooth - they also squeak when you squeeze them - so they are perfect for a teething infant.  He does not grow bored of them too quickly because there are 12 of them, so he usually goes through chewing and squeezing each one of them before he throws them all over the place.  Then we just stack them up and start all over again (he also loves to knock them down after stacked).  They are great if you want something different from the normal teething rings and toys for teething babies.  They also have little animal pictures, designs and numbers on them so they have that added educational quality as well allowing them to be used in the later years.  To boot, they are very inexpensive - so all around, it is a win-win!

text: I bought this set of blocks after seeing them in a baby store. As parents, we are making a concerted effort not to buy toys made in China.  The tag affixed to the product (the square tag shown in the product picture) says it is "Manufactured by Battat, Inc." in Plattsburgh, NY or Montreal, P.Q.  I was excited to see a toy product not made in China and with the possibility of it manufactured in New York State (I am from NYS)! It wasn't until I brought the product home when I noticed the back-side of the tag said "Made in China!"  How can these blocks be manufactured by a company located in Plattsburgh or Montreal but made in China?  I called the customer service number and representative told me the blocks are made in China but the TAG is made in Plattsburgh??  Huh??? First of all, why would I care where the tag was made? My child will be playing with the blocks, not the tag.  And secondly, I find the whole situation very misleading.  Why doesn't the tag say "Manufactured FOR Battat, Inc?"However, this set of blocks is quite nice.  They are easy to stack even though they are soft and rubbery.  They even have nice artistic detail to them.  Some of the block faces have animals, while others have numbers, and some have shapes.  They come in a convenient storage bag. My son likes to squeeze them to make them squeak.After a bit of contemplation, we decided to keep the product.  I am giving this product a 3-star rating because they initially mislead me into thinking they were made in the USA. Otherwise, this is a very nice product.
